SIMPLE: sham
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sham
<hw>Sham</hw> <pr>(sh⟦acr⟧m)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Originally the
same word as <ets>shame</ets>, hence, a disgrace, a trick. See
<er>Shame</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which
deceives expectation; any trick, fraud, or device that deludes and
disappoints; a make-believe; delusion; imposture; humbug.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧A
mere <xex>sham</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Bp. Stillingfleet.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Believe who will the solemn <qex>sham</qex>, not I.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A false front, or removable ornamental
covering.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Pillow sham</b></col>, <cd>a covering to be laid on a
pillow.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sham</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sham
<hw>Sham</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>False; counterfeit; pretended;
feigned; unreal; <as>as, a <ex>sham</ex> fight</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They scorned the <qex>sham</qex> independence proffered to them by
the Athenians.</q> <rj><qau>Jowett (Thucyd)</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sham</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Sham
<hw>Sham</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Shammed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Shamming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To trick; to cheat;
to deceive or delude with false pretenses.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fooled and <qex>shammed</qex> into a conviction.</q>
<rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To obtrude by fraud or imposition.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We must have a care that we do not . . . <qex>sham</qex> fallacies
upon the world for current reason.</q>
<rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To assume the manner and character of; to imitate;
to ape; to feign.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>To sham Abram</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To sham
Abraham</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to feign sickness; to malinger. Hence a
malingerer is called, in sailors' cant, <xex>Sham Abram</xex>, or
<xex>Sham Abraham</xex>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sham</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Sham
<hw>Sham</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To make false pretenses; to
deceive; to feign; to impose.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wondering . . . whether those who lectured him were such fools as
they professed to be, or were only <qex>shamming</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shama</ent>⟦br⟧
